## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Why it breaks

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ (`SYSLIB0006`). `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone. You must switch to **cooperative cancellation**.

### Pattern classification

| Usage | Pattern | Replacement |
|-------|---------|-------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | Timeout enforcement | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Remove — not needed with cooperative model |

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(
            token => work(),  // wrapper for legacy callers
            timeout);
    }

    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerException is OperationCanceledException
                                             && cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Details |
|---------|---------|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | The `Func<T>` overload (no token) keeps running in the background after timeout — it's fire-and-forget. The old `Thread.Abort` killed it mid-flight. Prefer the `Func<CancellationToken, T>` overload and check the token inside your work. |
| **Token must be checked** | Insert `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints in loops or between expensive steps. Without checks, cancellation is delayed indefinitely. |
| **CTS must be disposed** | `CancellationTokenSource` leaks timers if not disposed. Always `using`. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` filter distinguishes timeout from external cancellation. Without it you'd mask unrelated cancellations. |
| **`default(T)` nullability** | The old code used `T result = default` and returned it from a closure — a race condition the old version had too. The `Task.Run` approach eliminates this. |

### Example: cooperative work

```csharp
// Callers should prefer this overload for clean cancellation:
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in largeCollection)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return ComputeFinalResult();
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### If the work is truly uncooperative

If you're calling code you can't modify (no token support), the work **will keep running** after timeout. The only way to forcibly stop uncooperative code in modern .NET is to move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()`. There is no in-process equivalent of the old `Thread.Abort`.
